article.headline: Drake holds on, pulls off upset of No. 18 Iowa State
article.linkText: Drake's defensive stand sends No. 18 Cyclones to defeat
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Defense did it for Drake.

Drake held off Iowa State with three defensive stands in the final minute and handed the Cyclones (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) a rare loss at home, 63-61 Wednesday night.

"It basically boiled down to defense,'' Drake coach Lisa Stone said. "Had we rebounded a little bit better and lessened those second-chance opportunities, it might have put us in a little bit better situation.

"But we hung on with great defensive effort.''

Carla Bennett led Drake (2-0) with 15 points and sank one of two of free throws with 1:04 left to put the Bulldogs ahead to stay.

Iowa State (1-1), which had defeated Drake by 30 points each of the last two years, then failed on three chances to tie or take the lead. It was the Cyclones' first loss in a non-conference regular-season game at home since Drake won at Hilton Coliseum on Dec. 7, 1994.

"We had a lot of wide open shots that we missed,'' said Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly, who had been 39-0 against non-conference foes in the regular season. "With a team like we have, we have to execute to win and we didn't do that.''

Iowa State's Erica Junod was short on an open 3-pointer from the left side with 45 seconds to go and Lindsey Wilson's 15-footer bounced off the rim with 5 seconds to play.

Drake's Maureen Head hit one of two free throws with 3.9 seconds
left to make it 63-61 and Iowa State had one last chance, calling
time in the frontcourt with 2.6 seconds showing. But Wilson,
watching the clock all the way, shot after the buzzer sounded.

"We had a lead and it was like, 'You guys, we can't give this up. We cannot let them get the lead again or it's done,' '' Bennett said. "You just want to hold on to what you've got when it gets down to that.''

Freshman Nicole Denmon added 14 points for Drake, and Head
scored 12, going 3-for-4 from 3-point range. Head had made only one
3-pointer in her first two seasons at Drake.

"I didn't really know I was on the 3-point line,'' Head said.
"The coaches just tell all of us to shoot when we're open. I did
and it just happened to be on the 3-point line.''

Anne O'Neil led Iowa State with 16 points, while Wilson and Mary
Cofield scored 12 each.

Iowa State outrebounded Drake 39-29 but was 4-for-23 from
3-point range after making 13 3s against St. Francis on Sunday. The
Cyclones committed 19 turnovers, 13 in the first half.

Despite its ballhandling problems, Iowa State led 27-19 late in
the first half after an 11-2 run. Drake pulled to 33-29 at
halftime, when Linda Sayavongchanh hit a running jumper at the
buzzer, and took that momentum into the second half.

"We made some careless turnovers,'' Fennelly said. "A number
of those were lack of concentration. When you get called for three
seconds, that's not good defense. When you get called for an
illegal screen, that's not good defense, that's poor offense.

"Those are the things I'm responsible for and I have to make sure it gets done.''
